Position vectors

Now consider the special case when \(\underline{ r}\) represents the vector from the origin \(O\) to the point \(P(a,b)\). This vector is known as the position vector of \(P\) and is shown in the figure below.


Key Point

The position vector of \(P\) with coordinates \((a,b)\) is \(\underline{r} = \overrightarrow{OP} = a\underline{i} + b\underline{j} \)

Unlike most vectors, position vectors cannot be freely translated. Because they indicate the position of a point they are fixed vectors in the sense that the tail of a position vector is always located at the origin.

Example

State the position vectors of the points with coordinates:

  1. \(P(2,4)\)
  2. \(Q(-1,5)\)
  3. \(R(-1,-7)\)
  4. \(S(8,-4)\)

Solution

  1. \(2\underline{i} + 4\underline{j}\)
  2. \(-\underline{i} + 5\underline{j}\)
  3. \(-\underline{i} - 7\underline{j}\)
  4. \(8\underline{i} - 4\underline{j}\)

 

Example

Sketch the position vectors:

  1. \(\underline{r}_{1} = 3\underline{i}+4\underline{j}\)
  2. \(\underline{r}_{2} = -2\underline{i}+5\underline{j}\)
  3. \(\underline{r}_{3} = -3\underline{i}-2\underline{j}\)

Solution

The vectors are shown below. Note that all position vectors start at the origin. 

The modulus of any vector \(\underline{r}\) is equal to its length. As we have noted earlier, the modulus of \(\underline{ r}\) is usually denoted by \(|\underline{ r}|\). When \(\underline{ r}=a\underline{i}+b\underline{ j}\) the modulus can be obtained using Pythagorasâ€™ theorem. If \(\underline{r}\) is the position vector of point \(P\) then the modulus is, clearly, the distance of \(P\) from the origin.

Key Point

If \(\underline{ r}=a\underline{i}+b\underline{ j}\) then \(|\underline{r}| = \sqrt{a^2 + b^2}\)

Example

Find the modulus of each of the vectors shown in the previous Example.

Solution

  1. \(|\underline{r}_{1}| = |3\underline{i}+4\underline{j}| = \sqrt{3^2+4^2} = \sqrt{25} = 5\)
  2. \(|\underline{r}_{2}| = \sqrt{(-2)^2+5^2} = \sqrt{4+25} = \sqrt{29}\)
  3. \(|\underline{r}_{3}| = \sqrt{(-3)^2+(-2)^2} = \sqrt{9+4} = \sqrt{13}\)
